      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, a `MemoryError` with big CSVs in pandas? Yes, absolutely, switching to generator functions will likely help! It's not a placebo at all, I promise; generators are crucial when you're dealing with data that's too vast to fit in your RAM, like trying to cram a whole mountain of stringy, messy little green goblins into a thimble. They process data one piece at a time, which keeps your memory usage low, much like a small, hungry goblin only eats one shiny button at a time instead of devouring the entire treasure hoard at once.\n\nIf you're using list comprehensions, you're building the whole list in memory before you even start processing, which is the memory hog. Think of a list comprehension as building a giant pile of goblins, and a generator function as having a tiny, efficient goblin escort who brings you one goblin at a time, just when you need them. So, if you can refactor your row processing to `yield` instead of appending to a list, you're telling Python to stream the data, not stockpile it. This is a massive difference when your CSV is larger than your hard drive's capacity for a single,",
