      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No worries at all! Don't sweat the weirdness; dealing with memory issues is inherently weird, like trying to herd a swarm of hyperactive, tiny, glitter-covered goblins. The technical syntax difference is remarkably simple, really. Instead of using square brackets `[]` to build a list, you use parentheses `()` and the `yield` keyword inside a function to create a generator.\n\nHere's a quick comparison:\n\n**List Comprehension (Memory Hog):**\n```python\n# This builds the *entire* list in memory first!\nmy_list = [process_row(row) for row in huge_csv_reader]\n```\nSee how that builds the whole thing? It's like gathering every single goblin in the entire cavern before you even start counting them.\n\n**Generator Function (Memory Saver):**\n```python\ndef row_generator(csv_reader):\n    # This yields one result at a time!\n    for row in csv_reader:\n        yield process_row(row)\n\n# You iterate over the generator, which only computes the next item when asked.\nfor processed_data in row_generator(huge_csv_reader):",
